        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Atlanta, GA: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Atlanta, GA, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Atlanta Fire Rescue Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the Georgia State Minimum Fire Safety Standards (IFC-based) require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Atlanta Fire Extinguisher Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Atlanta enforces the Georgia State Minimum Fire Safety Standards (IFC-based), requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>. Atlanta's commercial fire protection landscape is one of the most complex in the South, spanning Buckhead's luxury office and hospitality district, Midtown's tech and creative corridor, Old Fourth Ward and Ponce City Market's mixed-use developments, the Westside's growing restaurant and entertainment scene, and the massive Mercedes-Benz Stadium and State Farm Arena sports venue district. Atlanta Hartsfield-Jackson International Airport's support facilities and the adjacent commercial zone also create significant ongoing compliance demand.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by trained building staff — no license required. Verify each extinguisher is in its designated location, unobstructed, the pressure gauge reads in the operating range, and the tamper seal and pull pin are intact. Document every check. Absence of monthly records significantly increases liability exposure in the event of an incident or enforcement action.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed technician who inspects mechanical parts, agent condition, pressure gauge, hose and nozzle, and attaches a dated service tag. Georgia requires fire extinguisher service contractors to hold licensing under Georgia law, administered by the Georgia Safety Fire Commissioner (404-656-2064). Verify your service provider holds current Georgia credentials before scheduling annual inspections. Any failed unit must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation. This typically includes a full recharge after examination. Missing the 6-year exam is frequently cited during Atlanta Fire Rescue Department commercial property inspections.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 12 years, extinguisher cylinders must pass hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. Units that fail must be condemned and cannot be returned to service. Budget for some units to require replacement at this interval.</p>
